```@raw html
<div class="markdown"><p>Following our previous tutorial in GNNs, we covered how to create graph neural networks.</p>
<p>In this tutorial, we will be learning how to use Graph Neural Networks &#40;GNNs&#41; for node classification. Given the ground-truth labels of only a small subset of nodes, and want to infer the labels for all the remaining nodes &#40;transductive learning&#41;.</p>
</div>
```

## Dataset: Cora
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">

<p>For our tutorial, we will be using the <code>Cora</code> dataset. <code>Cora</code> is a citaton network of 2708 documents classified into one of seven classes and 5429 links. Each node represent articles/documents and the edges between these nodes if one of them cite each other.</p>
<p>Each publication in the dataset is described by a 0/1-valued word vector indicating the absence/presence of the corresponding word from the dictionary. The dictionary consists of 1433 unique words.</p>
<p>This dataset was first introduced by <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1603.08861">Yang et al. &#40;2016&#41;</a> as one of the datasets of the <code>Planetoid</code> benchmark suite. We will be using <a href="https://juliaml.github.io/MLDatasets.jl/stable/">MLDatasets.jl</a> for an easy accss to this dataset.</p>
```

## Multi-layer Perception Network &#40;MLP&#41;
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">

<p>In theory, we should be able to infer the category of a document solely based on its content, <em>i.e.</em> its bag-of-words feature representation, without taking any relational information into account.</p>
<p>Let&#39;s verify that by constructing a simple MLP that solely operates on input node features &#40;using shared weights across all nodes&#41;:</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    struct MLP
        layers::NamedTuple
    end

    Flux.@functor MLP
    
    function MLP(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels; drop_rate=0.5)
        layers = (hidden = Dense(num_features =&gt; hidden_channels),
                    drop = Dropout(drop_rate),
                    classifier = Dense(hidden_channels =&gt; num_classes))
        return MLP(layers)
    end

    function (model::MLP)(x::AbstractMatrix)
        l = model.layers
        x = l.hidden(x)
        x = relu(x)
        x = l.drop(x)
        x = l.classifier(x)
        return x
    end
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><h3>Training a Multilayer Perceptron</h3>
<p>Our MLP is defined by two linear layers and enhanced by <a href="https://fluxml.ai/Flux.jl/stable/models/nnlib/#NNlib.relu">ReLU</a> non-linearity and <a href="https://fluxml.ai/Flux.jl/stable/models/layers/#Flux.Dropout">Dropout</a>. Here, we first reduce the 1433-dimensional feature vector to a low-dimensional embedding &#40;<code>hidden_channels&#61;16</code>&#41;, while the second linear layer acts as a classifier that should map each low-dimensional node embedding to one of the 7 classes.</p>
<p>Let&#39;s train our simple MLP by following a similar procedure as described in <a href="https://carlolucibello.github.io/GraphNeuralNetworks.jl/dev/tutorials/gnn_intro_pluto">the first part of this tutorial</a>. We again make use of the <strong>cross entropy loss</strong> and <strong>Adam optimizer</strong>. This time, we also define a <strong><code>accuracy</code> function</strong> to evaluate how well our final model performs on the test node set &#40;which labels have not been observed during training&#41;.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function train(model::MLP, data::AbstractMatrix, epochs::Int, opt, ps)
    Flux.trainmode!(model)

    for epoch in 1:epochs
        loss, gs = Flux.withgradient(ps) do
            ŷ = model(data)
            logitcrossentropy(ŷ[:, train_mask], y[:, train_mask])
        end
    
        Flux.Optimise.update!(opt, ps, gs)
        if epoch % 200 == 0
            @show epoch, loss
        end
    end
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-train' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>train (generic function with 1 method)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function accuracy(model::MLP, x::AbstractMatrix, y::Flux.OneHotArray, mask::BitVector)
    Flux.testmode!(model)
    mean(onecold(model(x))[mask] .== onecold(y)[mask])
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-accuracy' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>accuracy (generic function with 1 method)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    mlp = MLP(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels)
    ps_mlp = Flux.params(mlp)
    opt_mlp = ADAM(1e-3)
    epochs = 2000
    train(mlp, g.ndata.features, epochs, opt_mlp, ps_mlp)
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>After training the model, we can call the <code>accuracy</code> function to see how well our model performs on unseen labels. Here, we are interested in the accuracy of the model, <em>i.e.</em>, the ratio of correctly classified nodes:</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>accuracy(mlp, g.ndata.features, y, .!train_mask)</code></pre>
<pre id='var-hash179283' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>0.3383956386292835</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>As one can see, our MLP performs rather bad with only about 47&#37; test accuracy. But why does the MLP do not perform better? The main reason for that is that this model suffers from heavy overfitting due to only having access to a <strong>small amount of training nodes</strong>, and therefore generalizes poorly to unseen node representations.</p>
<p>It also fails to incorporate an important bias into the model: <strong>Cited papers are very likely related to the category of a document</strong>. That is exactly where Graph Neural Networks come into play and can help to boost the performance of our model.</p>
</div>


```
## Training a Graph Convolutional Neural Network &#40;GNN&#41;
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">

<p>We can easily convert our MLP to a GNN by swapping the <code>torch.nn.Linear</code> layers with PyG&#39;s GNN operators.</p>
<p>Following-up on <a href="">the first part of this tutorial</a>, we replace the linear layers by the <a href=""><code>GCNConv</code></a> module. To recap, the <strong>GCN layer</strong> &#40;<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1609.02907">Kipf et al. &#40;2017&#41;</a>&#41; is defined as</p>
<p class="tex">$$\mathbf&#123;x&#125;_v^&#123;&#40;\ell &#43; 1&#41;&#125; &#61; \mathbf&#123;W&#125;^&#123;&#40;\ell &#43; 1&#41;&#125; \sum_&#123;w \in \mathcal&#123;N&#125;&#40;v&#41; \, \cup \, \&#123; v \&#125;&#125; \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;c_&#123;w,v&#125;&#125; \cdot \mathbf&#123;x&#125;_w^&#123;&#40;\ell&#41;&#125;$$</p>
<p>where <span class="tex">$\mathbf&#123;W&#125;^&#123;&#40;\ell &#43; 1&#41;&#125;$</span> denotes a trainable weight matrix of shape <code>&#91;num_output_features, num_input_features&#93;</code> and <span class="tex">$c_&#123;w,v&#125;$</span> refers to a fixed normalization coefficient for each edge. In contrast, a single <code>Linear</code> layer is defined as</p>
<p class="tex">$$\mathbf&#123;x&#125;_v^&#123;&#40;\ell &#43; 1&#41;&#125; &#61; \mathbf&#123;W&#125;^&#123;&#40;\ell &#43; 1&#41;&#125; \mathbf&#123;x&#125;_v^&#123;&#40;\ell&#41;&#125;$$</p>
<p>which does not make use of neighboring node information.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin 
    struct GCN
        layers::NamedTuple
    end
    
    Flux.@functor GCN # provides parameter collection, gpu movement and more



    function GCN(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels; drop_rate=0.5)
        layers = (conv1 = GCNConv(num_features =&gt; hidden_channels),
                    drop = Dropout(drop_rate), 
                    conv2 = GCNConv(hidden_channels =&gt; num_classes))
        return GCN(layers)
    end

    function (gcn::GCN)(g::GNNGraph, x::AbstractMatrix)
        l = gcn.layers
        x = l.conv1(g, x)
        x = relu.(x)
        x = l.drop(x)
        x = l.conv2(g, x)
        return x
    end
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>Now let&#39;s visualize the node embeddings of our <strong>untrained</strong> GCN network.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    gcn = GCN(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels)
    h_untrained = gcn(g, x) |&gt; transpose
    visualize_tsne(h_untrained, g.ndata.targets)
end</code></pre>
<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,">


<div class="markdown"><p>We certainly can do better by training our model. The training and testing procedure is once again the same, but this time we make use of the node features <code>x</code> <strong>and</strong> the graph <code>g</code> as input to our GCN model.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function train(model::GCN, g::GNNGraph, x::AbstractMatrix, epochs::Int, ps, opt)
    Flux.trainmode!(model)

    for epoch in 1:epochs
        loss, gs = Flux.withgradient(ps) do
            ŷ = model(g, x)
            logitcrossentropy(ŷ[:,train_mask], y[:,train_mask])
        end
    
        Flux.Optimise.update!(opt, ps, gs)
        if epoch % 200 == 0
            @show epoch, loss
        end
    end
end
</code></pre>
<pre id='var-train' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>train (generic function with 2 methods)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function accuracy(model::GCN, g::GNNGraph, x::AbstractMatrix, y::Flux.OneHotArray, mask::BitVector)
    Flux.testmode!(model)
    mean(onecold(model(g, x))[mask] .== onecold(y)[mask])
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-accuracy' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>accuracy (generic function with 2 methods)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    ps_gcn = Flux.params(gcn)
    opt_gcn = ADAM(1e-2)
    train(gcn, g, x, epochs, ps_gcn, opt_gcn)
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>Now let&#39;s evaluate the loss of our trained GCN.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>with_terminal() do
    train_accuracy = accuracy(gcn, g, g.ndata.features, y, train_mask)
    test_accuracy = accuracy(gcn, g, g.ndata.features, y,  .!train_mask)
    
    println("Train accuracy: $(train_accuracy)")
    println("Test accuracy: $(test_accuracy)")
end</code></pre>
<pre id="plutouiterminal">
Train accuracy: 1.0
Test accuracy: 0.757398753894081
</pre>



<div class="markdown"><p><strong>There it is&#33;</strong> By simply swapping the linear layers with GNN layers, we can reach <strong>75.77&#37; of test accuracy</strong>&#33; This is in stark contrast to the 59&#37; of test accuracy obtained by our MLP, indicating that relational information plays a crucial role in obtaining better performance.</p>
<p>We can also verify that once again by looking at the output embeddings of our trained model, which now produces a far better clustering of nodes of the same category.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    Flux.testmode!(gcn) # inference mode

    out_trained = gcn(g, x) |&gt; transpose
    visualize_tsne(out_trained, g.ndata.targets)
end</code></pre>
<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,">
```
